# Best Practices for Teaching with micro:bit

#### Physical computing offers an exciting and interactive approach to involve students in coding, and with thoughtful consideration, your lessons can be seamlessly executed.

## Before the lesson

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">🗃️ Organization tips</summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>


<img src="https://images.code.org/8c5598c604dc9e7a0e4edcf01d5b7244-image-1707322034881.png" alt="storage container for micro:bit" width="160px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 40px 40px;">

- #### Label the micro:bits to keep track of them easily.

- #### Store micro:bits in their original anti-static pouch to keep them safe.

- #### Get creative with storage options for multiple micro:bits, like purchasing containers to organize them and their accessories.
</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">✍🏽 Preparation </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/a99418675b349371703fe1ed4b821fc4-image-1707407730242.png" alt="two micro:bits with faces" width="160px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 20px;">

- #### **Review the lesson plans in the selected pathway beforehand.** Familiarize yourself with the lessons and consider areas where students might need extra help.

- #### Plan for how the devices will be distributed among your students. 

- #### Practice the lessons.  
</p></div>
</details>


## During the lesson

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">💭 Relate to familiar concepts </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/f97e7a0677c60156fdd380843c4fc2ea-image-1707322374547.png" alt="micro:bit on a shoe with a one on it" width="160px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: -20px 40px 0px 20px;">

- #### Use familiar examples and real-life situations to explain micro:bit concepts in a way that students can relate to.

- #### Review coding concepts that have been previously taught in the CSF pathway and remind students that these apply when coding their micro:bits. 


</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">🎨 Encourage Creativity </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/613d33bfaf85b3d47b95e2ad96c84c8d-image-1707323049639.png" alt="students holding a micro:bit" width="160px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 40px;">


- #### Unlike some of the coding levels on the Code.org platform, MakeCode does not automatically check your code to let you move on. This allows students to come up with creative or unique solutions. 
- #### Encourage students to be creative and explore the possibilities. 
- #### Celebrate perseverance and trying new things, even if it doesn't always work.

</p></div>
</details>

<details style="background-color: #ececec; padding: 10px; margin-bottom: 10px; border: 1px solid transparent; border-radius: 5px;">
    <summary style="font-size: 1.5em; font-weight: bold;">🧑‍🏫 Facilitating the Lesson </summary>
<div style="margin-top: 20px; margin-left: 20px; margin-right: 20px;">
    <p>

<img src="https://images.code.org/0fa0e524a2e581105f69df060126cf8c-image-1707408688944.png" alt="students holding a micro:bit" width="160px" style="border-radius:10px; float:right; margin: 0 40px 0px 40px;">

- #### **Use the virtual micro:bit.** MakeCode has a virtual micro:bit embedded on the site for students to test their code while they are programming. It is a great tool if you have limited devices or if you want students to practice coding first. 

- #### **Implement pair programming strategies.** Assign one student to be the driver and another as the navigator. Set a timer and allow the students to switch roles. 

- #### **Encourage discussion.** Enrich learning experiences by adding discussion and sharing amongst students. Students can  demo their projects and discuss challenges and successes with the process.
</details>
 


